{"title_page": "Nomafrench Mbombo", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n| name               = Nomafrench Mbombo\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| honorific-suffix   = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament|MPP]]\n| image              = Nomafrench Mbombo.png\n| image_size         = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Mbombo in 2019\n| office             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Health]]\n| premier            = [[Alan Winde]]<br>[[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start         = 1 January 2015\n| term_end           = \n| predecessor        = [[Theuns Botha]]\n| successor          = \n| office1            = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Federal Leader of the Democratic Alliance Women's Network]]\n| deputy1            = Safiyia Stanfley\n| term_start1        = 7 April 2018\n| term_end1          = \n| predecessor1       = [[Denise Robinson]]\n| office2            = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Cultural Affairs and Sport]]\n| premier2           = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2        = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2          = 1 January 2015\n| predecessor2       = [[Ivan Meyer]]\n| successor2         = [[Theuns Botha]]\n| office3            = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start3        = 21 May 2014\n| term_end3          = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1966|09|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mdantsane]], [[East London]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = South African \n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2013\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = \n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = 2\n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = Politician\n| profession         = \n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Nomafrench Mbombo''' (born 6 September 1966) is a South African academic and politician who has been serving as the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Health]] since her appointment in 2015. She has also been serving as a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] since the provincial election of 2014. She had previously served as the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Cultural Affairs and Sport]] from 2014 to 2015. Mbombo is the Federal Leader of the Democratic Alliance Women's Network. She is a member of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA).<ref>[https://www.da.org.za/people/nomafrench-mbombo Nomafrench Mbombo]. ''Democratic Alliance''. Retrieved on 3 January 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/gov_employee/professor-nomafrench-mbombo Professor Nomafrench Mbombo]. ''Western Cape Government''. Retrieved on 3 January 2019.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMbombo was born on 6 September 1966. She spent her childhood in the [[Mdantsane]] township of [[East London, Eastern Cape|East London]] in the now-dissolved [[Cape Province]].<ref name=\"Appointment\">[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/premier-helen-zille-announces-new-cabinet Premier Helen Zille Announces New Cabinet]. ''Western Cape Government''. Retrieved on 3 January 2019.</ref>\n\nShe obtained her PhD in the fields of Gender and Human Rights from the [[University of the Western Cape]]. She achieved her Masters in Maternal and Child Health from the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]], and her Bachelors in Nursing Science from the [[University of Fort Hare]]. She was then employed in both the Eastern Cape and KwaZulu-Natal provincial and local government health departments.<ref name=\"Appointment\" />\n\nBefore being involved in politics, she worked as an Associate Professor at the Faculty of Community and Health Sciences Department of the University of the Western Cape.<ref name=\"Appointment\" />\n\nShe has also served as a member of various organisations, such as the National Committee of Confidential Enquiries on Maternal Death, NEPAD, and the UN Office of Human Rights: Women & Gender Directorate.<ref name=\"Appointment\" />\n==Political career==\nMbombo, who previously was an [[African National Congress]] supporter, joined the DA in 2013, after attending a DA meeting of black professionals.<ref name =\"spotlight\">{{cite news |last1=Huisman |first1=Bi\u00e9nne |title=Mbombo: From domestic worker to MEC |url=https://www.spotlightnsp.co.za/2019/08/29/mbombo-from-domestic-worker-to-mec/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |newspaper=spotlightnsp.co.za |date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nMbombo was elected to the Western Cape Provincial Parliament in 2014. She was sworn in as a Member on 21 May 2014. She represents the [[Philippi, Cape Town|Philippi]] region of the [[City of Cape Town]]. Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed Mbombo to the post of Western Cape Provincial Minister of Cultural Affairs and Sport. She was sworn in as Provincial Minister on 26 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.pa.org.za/person/nomafrench-mbombo/ Dr Nomafrench Mbombo]. ''People's Assembly''. Retrieved on 3 January 2019.</ref>\n[[File:\"Verlorenvlei Heritage Settlement\" MEC Nomafrench Mbombo at unveiling of plaque..jpg|left|200px|thumb|Mbombo unveiling a plaque in September 2014]]\nIn December 2014, Premier Helen Zille announced that [[Theuns Botha]] and Mbombo would exchange ministerial positions. Mbombo would now become Western Cape Provincial Minister of Health, while Botha would become Western Cape Provincial Minister of Cultural Affairs and Sport. The changes came into effect on 1 January 2015.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Zille-cracks-whip-in-Cabinet-reshuffle-20141231 Zille cracks whip in Cabinet reshuffle]. ''News24''. Retrieved on 3 January 2019.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, incumbent Democratic Alliance Women's Network Federal Leader, [[Denise Robinson]], announced that she would not seek re-election to another term. Mbombo subsequently declared her candidacy and was elected on 7 April 2018 at the 2018 Democratic Alliance Federal Congress.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/04/06/da-federal-council-meets-ahead-of-party-congress DA Federal Council meets ahead of party congress]. ''EWN''. Retrieved on 3 January 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-04-07-new-da-womens-network-leader-pays-tribute-to-domestic-abuse-victims/ New DA Women's Network leader pays tribute to domestic abuse victims]. ''Mail & Guardian''. Retrieved on 3 January 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, newly-elected Premier [[Alan Winde]] announced that he had retained Mbombo in her post as Provincial Minister of Health.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new]. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, she declared her candidacy for interim Federal Chairperson of the Democratic Alliance following [[Athol Trollip]]'s resignation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ndamase |first1=Mkhululi |title=Mdantsane's Mbombo in running as interim DA federal chair |url=https://www.dispatchlive.co.za/news/2019-11-04-mdantsanes-mbombo-in-running-as-interim-da-federal-chair/ |accessdate=14 November 2019 |newspaper=HeraldLIVE |date=4 November 2019}}</ref> She lost to [[Ivan Meyer]].<ref>{{cite news |title=John Steenhuisen wins DA interim leader position |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/breaking-news/2205737/john-steenhuisen-wins-da-interim-leader-position/ |accessdate=17 November 2019 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n==Personal life==\nMbombo was married and has two daughters. Her husband died in 2003.<ref name=\"spotlight\" />\n\nIn March 2020, Mbombo came into contact with the French consul-general [[Laurent Amar]] who tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shange |first1=Naledi |title=Western Cape health MEC self-isolating after French consul general tests positive |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-03-18-western-cape-health-mec-self-isolating-after-french-consul-general-tests-positive/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=18 March 2020}}</ref> She subsequently went into [[self-isolation]] and later tested negative.<ref>{{cite news |title=Western Cape Health MEC Nomafrench Mbombo tests negative for Covid-19 |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/western-cape-health-mec-nomafrench-mbombo-tests-negative-for-covid-19-45234989 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |agency=IOL |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Denise Robinson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Federal Leader of the Democratic Alliance Women's Network|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Theuns Botha]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Western Cape Provincial Minister of Health|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ivan Meyer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Western Cape Provincial Minister of Cultural Affairs and Sport|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Theuns Botha]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Democratic Alliance (South Africa)}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mbombo, Nomafrench}}\n[[Category: Living people]]\n[[Category: Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category: Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category: Xhosa people]]\n[[Category: Women members of provincial legislatures of 